Time to put these espresso mugs in the glaze kiln, but first I need to scrape some glaze. I prefer to glaze the whole cup rather then waxing the bottoms, mainly because I’m I’m too messy with the wax. It always ends up where I don’t want it to be! The good news is those scrapings are all recycled back into glaze so no waste is produced🌟 #ceramics #pottery #asmr #process #glazingpottery

Apricity, a now obsolete but underrated word meaning the warmth of the sun on a winters day. Heres a little gold luster hack I’ve only recently learned due to a section of my kiln that just refuses to vent properly. 

When gold luster doesn’t have enough ventilation while firing it can do some pretty weird looking stuff to your items. And by weird I mean dull looking sections, cloudiness, and a sort of soot stained after effect. It’s upsetting… especially when you know how much gold costs 🫠

If this has ever happened to you, you might think to yourself “You win some, you looses some.”
HA- not anymore! 

Just get a nice silver polishing cloth and gently rub the gold areas to remove the tarnish. I hate to say it’s as simple as that, but honestly it really is. 

#ceramics #oddlysatisfying #pottery #goldluster

Gotta love that fluorescent lighting when the sun outside won’t come out to play 🌞

I always find throwing more difficult during the colder months of the year— somehow the boiling throwing water always turns freezing in an instant. Cold hands and cold clay, they just don’t mix. 
I’m so excited it’s finally getting warm again though! Kilns are firing around the clock, when the weather allows of course, and I almost have a perfect humidity free zone. (If you’re in Atlanta you know what kind of an accomplishment that really is!) 

I threw this 8 pound English porcelain vase last month but was too nervous it wouldn’t survive the kiln firings— Happy to report it made it through the bisque and I hope the glaze fire today treats her well today. 
Wish me luck 🍀 #wheelthrowing #potteryvideos #porcelain #oddlysatisfying #art #potterywheelthrowing #ceramics

A porcelain ring dish, from start to finish! 

Okay, perhaps there are a few steps missing 🔥 Aka each ring dish spending 3 full days in the kiln!

We start with a bucket of hand mixed porcelain slip and pour it into a plaster mold (made from my original design, of course). It will sit there for almost 30 min before it’s ready to go on to next steps of dumping the left over slip and cutting off the top to make it nice and smooth. 

I have a fancy way of finishing the dishes before they’re ready to go into the bisque, perhaps you could convince me to share my secret 😜.
After the bisque fire, it will take a trip into the glaze bucket, and then right back into another firing, but this time much hotter. 🔥

Last step is to add the gold or silver luster and decals that make the ring dish what you know and love 💕. It will spend its last day in the kiln before it’s ready to be loved by you!

Talk nice to your glaze and the kiln gods will bless 🙏

No but really, glazing large pots is tricky, especially if you’re not using a brushable glaze (a normal glaze with cmc gum mixed in). 
I like to dip glaze my large pots in two parts ✌️ starting with an internal pour that will coat the inside of the pot, and then a quick dunk in my glaze bucket.

Takes some strong fingers and a willing foot ring 😂 let’s see if these survive the kiln!

This iridescent luster on these handmade ornaments is my whole world now, I mean how could it not be! But it does require a tricky extra step and a full extra day in the kiln in order to make this magic happen. So let’s talk about it!

All ceramic items go through a minimum of 2 kiln firings (that’s not totally true but let’s not make this too complicated). 
The first is the bisque fire, which removes all water from the clay without taking it to its vitrification temp. 
The second is the glaze fire- the one that makes pottery fully vitrified (ideally) and food safe.

All my work goes through a further third firing- the luster fire! This firing is lower in temp and essentially melts the gold luster onto the glaze. 

Okay, that’s all great, but this iridescent luster requires a whole 4th firing- can you believe it!?! That’s a hell of a long time to be in a kiln! 

It starts off as a sharp blue color that needs to be painted super fast in order to get the right patterning. Once it dried, it goes into the kiln for a day and becomes the iridescent shimmer we all love!

Hi, I’m Sophia!
I’m a 31 year old potter living in Atlanta, Ga.

I originally went to school for archaeology, but all my classes got dropped one semester (technical glitch) and the only classes available to me were art classes! 
Turned out to be one of the best things to ever happen to me! I took one pottery class and I was hooked!
7 years later and im still potting 🏺 

My grandmother is a stained glass artist and was a working artist my whole life. My Mimi is a huge inspiration for me, as she showed me being a working artist is not only possible, but just what use Keys girls do :)

I’m so grateful I get to be a potter and make yall items you can bring into your daily rituals. I can’t imagine my life any other way ♥️♥️♥️ #artist #pottery #art #meettheartist

The best memories are made @russianteatimerestaurant and that is certainly true for me! 

My weekends growing up in Chicago were spent downtown at the Art Institute for a quick spin around the museum (and I became an artist-go figure) and then right after we got to get tea and Borscht from, you guessed it, Russian Tea Time!

Russian Tea Time is so ingrained in my memory that after a decade of having not visited Chicago, I knew exactly how to get from the Orange Line to Russian Tea Time. Like I was autopilot! 

Im so honored to have been asked to make some bowls for the restaurant!

If youre in the Chicago area, make sure to stop by and have a tea (or vodka 😉) for me!
